WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.920 --> 00:00:05.320
Prof: Here we are,
talking about--recapitulating

00:00:05.320 --> 00:00:09.882
the work done on--
in reading part of the poem,

00:00:09.882 --> 00:00:12.500
selections of this poem.
 

00:00:12.500 --> 00:00:18.945
It's a little difficult;
of course, I'm not going to

00:00:18.945 --> 00:00:21.660
tell you exactly what we have
been talking about.

00:00:21.660 --> 00:00:26.822
We have been reading from the
work outside of the Divine

00:00:26.822 --> 00:00:29.168
Comedy;
we started there with the

00:00:29.168 --> 00:00:32.164
Vita nuova,
which we read as you recall,

00:00:32.164 --> 00:00:36.103
as a visionary text,
as a story of an education,

00:00:36.103 --> 00:00:40.685
as an autobiography and we
tried to explore what those

00:00:40.685 --> 00:00:45.180
terms mean and how they interact
with each other.

00:00:45.180 --> 00:00:48.360
How does one term shed light on
the other?

00:00:48.360 --> 00:00:51.962
What does it mean to write an
autobiography and at the same

00:00:51.962 --> 00:00:53.640
time having an education?
 

00:00:53.640 --> 00:00:57.776
The two converge,
of course, in Dante's

00:00:57.776 --> 00:00:59.300
imagination.
 

00:00:59.300 --> 00:01:02.698
You can only write an
education--a story of your

00:01:02.698 --> 00:01:07.400
education if you have a sense of
what your whole life is about.

00:01:07.400 --> 00:01:12.230
If you have some pattern of
coherence and intelligibility

00:01:12.230 --> 00:01:15.682
that you can impose on,
and extract from,

00:01:15.682 --> 00:01:19.220
respectively,
the sense of your life.

00:01:19.220 --> 00:01:22.840
But above all,
I was interested in that

00:01:22.840 --> 00:01:25.741
partial,
because it's sort of--it's

00:01:25.741 --> 00:01:29.230
truncated at the end as a sort
of interruption--

00:01:29.230 --> 00:01:32.203
deliberate interruption,
because what kind of

00:01:32.203 --> 00:01:33.959
preparation it gives us.
 

00:01:33.959 --> 00:01:38.897
To what extent is it repeated
that adventure Dante narrates in

00:01:38.897 --> 00:01:43.995
the Vita nuova is kind of
an adumbration of the Divine

00:01:43.995 --> 00:01:45.209
Comedy?
 

00:01:45.209 --> 00:01:49.703
In many ways the two texts
really are implicating each

00:01:49.703 --> 00:01:55.129
other in the sense that Dante
finishes the Vita nuova--

00:01:55.129 --> 00:01:57.319
stops writing the Vita
nuova,

00:01:57.319 --> 00:02:01.314
that's the inconclusive,
the unfinished quality of the

00:02:01.314 --> 00:02:04.783
text so that he can go on
writing the Divine

00:02:04.783 --> 00:02:07.328
Comedy,
if you see what I'm saying.

00:02:07.328 --> 00:02:10.990
The Vita nuova ends with
the statement of a project,

00:02:10.990 --> 00:02:15.010
of a project to come,
which therefore will be in a

00:02:15.010 --> 00:02:19.854
certain way the fulfillment of
what is only hinted at in the

00:02:19.854 --> 00:02:21.658
Vita nuova.
 

00:02:21.658 --> 00:02:25.220
The two texts are literally one
is preparing for the other,

00:02:25.220 --> 00:02:27.870
the other one--then the
Divine Comedy turns out the

00:02:27.870 --> 00:02:30.520
way we were reading the
Divine Comedy last time.

00:02:30.520 --> 00:02:36.490
The Divine Comedy itself
has a sort of inconclusive

00:02:36.490 --> 00:02:38.479
quality about it.
 

00:02:38.479 --> 00:02:44.199
Dante reaches and experiences
the beatific vision,

00:02:44.199 --> 00:02:51.800
and yet his text succumbs to
the enormity of the task of

00:02:51.800 --> 00:02:55.792
describing it,
and there were a number of

00:02:55.792 --> 00:02:58.128
reasons why we said Dante does
that.

00:02:58.128 --> 00:03:02.038
What seems to be,
and is, a defeat at the level

00:03:02.038 --> 00:03:07.219
of the imagination turns out to
be a great triumph for Dante's

00:03:07.219 --> 00:03:09.258
own theology,
right?

00:03:09.258 --> 00:03:13.318
The measure in which that the
poem ends in a kind of defeat,

00:03:13.318 --> 00:03:17.631
in sort of the--with the
admission of the impossibility

00:03:17.631 --> 00:03:20.693
for Dante--
the poet's language to contain

00:03:20.693 --> 00:03:25.165
and therefore reify,
circumscribe that which he has

00:03:25.165 --> 00:03:26.460
seen, right?
 

00:03:26.460 --> 00:03:31.766
He's sort of ending with this
question mark,

00:03:31.766 --> 00:03:37.940
this vision of effigy as he
says, our own image.

00:03:37.940 --> 00:03:42.020
That's all that is left for him
to recall,

00:03:42.020 --> 00:03:47.598
which really means that--in the
refusal to pinpoint,

00:03:47.598 --> 00:03:50.639
describe, and define the so
called beatific vision,

00:03:50.639 --> 00:03:52.520
some people could be very
disappointed;

00:03:52.520 --> 00:03:54.639
why doesn't he tell us what he
really saw?

00:03:54.639 --> 00:03:57.990
Because that would be the
statement valid for him;

00:03:57.990 --> 00:04:01.296
he wants us,
at the end of the poem to

00:04:01.296 --> 00:04:04.418
adventure,
to take our own journey and

00:04:04.418 --> 00:04:08.913
make our own discoveries about
that which remains the essential

00:04:08.913 --> 00:04:11.669
point of the Divine
Comedy,

00:04:11.669 --> 00:04:16.101
as is the essential point of
all great texts about tradition:

00:04:16.101 --> 00:04:19.720
the encounter between the human
and the Divine.

00:04:19.720 --> 00:04:22.540
That is the point of all the
great epics.

00:04:22.540 --> 00:04:27.163
Whether it is in the form
the Aeneid where the hero

00:04:27.163 --> 00:04:31.949
is always uncertain about what
the gods are telling him,

00:04:31.949 --> 00:04:37.076
uncertain as how to decipher
it, and yet he nonetheless

00:04:37.076 --> 00:04:41.620
pursues what he takes to be--
and makes mistakes--Aeneas,

00:04:41.620 --> 00:04:45.279
along the way--
but what he takes to be God's

00:04:45.279 --> 00:04:45.839
will.
 

00:04:45.839 --> 00:04:49.470
This is the way he can live out
his own sense of ethical

00:04:49.470 --> 00:04:52.084
imperative to himself,
to his people,

00:04:52.084 --> 00:04:56.221
the refugees that are coming
from Asia Minor and going toward

00:04:56.221 --> 00:04:59.851
an unknown land,
and the Divine imperative,

00:04:59.851 --> 00:05:05.223
or whether it's going to be the
renaissance text from Spencer's

00:05:05.223 --> 00:05:10.524
Fairy Queen to Tasso's,
to Milton, to Lucretius,

00:05:10.524 --> 00:05:13.860
who writes in a theological
epic.

00:05:13.860 --> 00:05:19.370
The idea he wants to cure his
readers,

00:05:19.370 --> 00:05:21.819
he has one reader in mind:
the young epicurean,

00:05:21.819 --> 00:05:24.319
and this is Lucretius,
whom Dante had never read--

00:05:24.319 --> 00:05:28.410
he read in parts and was very
fascinated by what he read,

00:05:28.410 --> 00:05:30.579
who wants to educate one young
man,

00:05:30.579 --> 00:05:35.434
Manaus, a young epicurean to
the real and bitter truth of

00:05:35.434 --> 00:05:40.810
what the epicurean philosophy
may be and that bitter truth,

00:05:40.810 --> 00:05:44.406
the harsh truth--Lucretius
thinks that there is no such

00:05:44.406 --> 00:05:44.940
thing.
 

00:05:44.940 --> 00:05:50.190
That ours--the Roman world is a
desecrated world,

00:05:50.190 --> 00:05:52.500
that the gods have fled,
that's the--

00:05:52.500 --> 00:05:55.000
but that is still in the mode
of an atheist,

00:05:55.000 --> 00:05:59.213
it is still a theological
concern because the implication

00:05:59.213 --> 00:06:03.425
of what I'm saying is that
atheism itself may be a way of

00:06:03.425 --> 00:06:05.601
addressing,
of course, it's a way of

00:06:05.601 --> 00:06:08.559
addressing the question of God,
the un-knowability of God,

00:06:08.559 --> 00:06:12.180
the distance of God,
maybe the non-existence of the

00:06:12.180 --> 00:06:12.629
gods.
 

00:06:12.629 --> 00:06:16.064
The Divine Comedy from
this point of view partakes of

00:06:16.064 --> 00:06:17.870
this extraordinary tradition.
 

00:06:17.870 --> 00:06:22.379
But he does it in a way which
is remarkably different;

00:06:22.379 --> 00:06:25.358
Dante does his theology in a
way which is remarkably

00:06:25.358 --> 00:06:28.863
different from anything else
that has gone on before him and,

00:06:28.863 --> 00:06:30.500
in many ways,
after him.

00:06:30.500 --> 00:06:33.620
I think there is a mode of
recapitulation,

00:06:33.620 --> 00:06:36.937
this is what I have to--I will
have to briefly illustrate and

00:06:36.937 --> 00:06:40.422
give you the chance to ask more
questions specifically about the

00:06:40.422 --> 00:06:40.920
poem.
 

00:06:40.920 --> 00:06:44.848
Some of these things that I
have said to you--the whole poem

00:06:44.848 --> 00:06:47.379
moves towards this kind of
theology.

00:06:47.379 --> 00:06:51.497
Condensed in Canto XXXIII of
Paradise,

00:06:51.497 --> 00:06:54.120
recapitulated right there.
 

00:06:54.120 --> 00:06:57.994
Of course Inferno goes
on talking about issues of

00:06:57.994 --> 00:07:00.244
politics,
which is not that they are

00:07:00.244 --> 00:07:03.574
easy, they are very complicated,
but in some ways they are

00:07:03.574 --> 00:07:05.490
rooted in Dante's own theology.
 

00:07:05.490 --> 00:07:07.281
That is, it's too easy to
believe that,

00:07:07.281 --> 00:07:09.500
you know, this is politics,
this is theology;

00:07:09.500 --> 00:07:12.009
they are always implicated with
one another.

00:07:12.009 --> 00:07:15.004
In fact, sometimes the best way
to understand the theology is to

00:07:15.004 --> 00:07:17.829
talk about the politics,
and the best way to understand

00:07:17.829 --> 00:07:20.449
the politics is to really talk
about the theology.

00:07:20.449 --> 00:07:25.360
They are completely,
always implicating each other.

00:07:25.360 --> 00:07:28.581
Inferno talks about the
ethics and the politics,

00:07:28.581 --> 00:07:32.399
Purgatorio talks about
aesthetics and ethics above all.

00:07:32.399 --> 00:07:38.490
The possibility of
reconstructing the human beings;

00:07:38.490 --> 00:07:42.827
so flawed they seem to be,
so incredibly sunk into the

00:07:42.827 --> 00:07:47.329
ditches of their own
perversions, of our perversions.

00:07:47.329 --> 00:07:51.336
How do you--so radical,
Dante's condemnation of the

00:07:51.336 --> 00:07:53.983
political realities,
of civil war,

00:07:53.983 --> 00:07:56.089
people cannibalizing each
other,

00:07:56.089 --> 00:07:58.290
and not in a metaphor that man
is a wolf to man,

00:07:58.290 --> 00:08:00.509
but literally they are doing
this.

00:08:00.509 --> 00:08:02.120
How do you get out of it?
 

00:08:02.120 --> 00:08:05.954
It's very difficult to be
so--to ostracize politics from

00:08:05.954 --> 00:08:09.790
the possibility of the human
imagination and then at one

00:08:09.790 --> 00:08:12.649
point saying,
well I still need this.

00:08:12.649 --> 00:08:15.333
How are you going to make a
persuasive case for your

00:08:15.333 --> 00:08:15.860
readers?
 

00:08:15.860 --> 00:08:21.769
This was the great challenge of
Purgatorio.

00:08:21.769 --> 00:08:27.839
We saw the question of time,
the great problem of freedom,

00:08:27.839 --> 00:08:31.499
that all of a sudden seemed to
surface in Purgatorio

00:08:31.499 --> 00:08:33.760
with Cato's suicide,
you remember,

00:08:33.760 --> 00:08:38.075
with the debate about the soul,
and created freedom,

00:08:38.075 --> 00:08:44.193
and by an act of freedom,
God's freedom to the attainment

00:08:44.193 --> 00:08:45.980
of the free will.
 

00:08:45.980 --> 00:08:49.450
Around this extraordinary
concern of freedom,

00:08:49.450 --> 00:08:52.899
and therefore the possibilities
of the moral life,

00:08:52.899 --> 00:08:58.928
we came to the conclusion of
Purgatorio with a garden,

00:08:58.928 --> 00:09:02.399
the Garden of Eden,
the place of pleasures,

00:09:02.399 --> 00:09:06.629
the place where pleasures are
not damned in and of themselves.

00:09:06.629 --> 00:09:09.710
The question becomes now,
because that is the Sabbath,

00:09:09.710 --> 00:09:14.128
that is the moment where
you--pleasure can be seen as the

00:09:14.128 --> 00:09:18.941
crown of work that which crowns,
the correlation of one's own

00:09:18.941 --> 00:09:20.259
labors and so on.
 

00:09:20.259 --> 00:09:23.320
That is also rooted in theology.
 

00:09:23.320 --> 00:09:26.595
Then we ended up in
Paradise where we really

00:09:26.595 --> 00:09:28.700
talked directly,
because I think that's really

00:09:28.700 --> 00:09:29.740
the substance of
Paradise,

00:09:29.740 --> 00:09:33.418
the possibility of thinking of
an aesthetic theology.

00:09:33.418 --> 00:09:36.070
How art and theology go hand in
hand,

00:09:36.070 --> 00:09:39.840
because what joins them is the
question of--

00:09:39.840 --> 00:09:43.168
not just the question of the
art being the temptation,

00:09:43.168 --> 00:09:46.399
ethical temptation,
but now the question of beauty

00:09:46.399 --> 00:09:49.168
as the mode of revelation of the
Divine.

00:09:49.168 --> 00:09:52.220
Therefore, the implication was,
and let's hope--

00:09:52.220 --> 00:09:56.929
I have said that very clearly,
that art becomes a way to know

00:09:56.929 --> 00:09:59.080
God,
a way to know the Divine,

00:09:59.080 --> 00:10:02.601
so we are moving away from
traditional assumptions about

00:10:02.601 --> 00:10:05.418
what is the path to go and
encounter God.

00:10:05.418 --> 00:10:08.370
What is really the discovery of
the Sacred;

00:10:08.370 --> 00:10:12.120
is the Sacred going to be
found, some texts in Dante seems

00:10:12.120 --> 00:10:15.740
to have believed that at some
point in a particular--

00:10:15.740 --> 00:10:18.783
in the animation of nature,
is it going to be found in the

00:10:18.783 --> 00:10:20.918
love that you have for your
Beatrice,

00:10:20.918 --> 00:10:24.639
or you, or Beatrice's for your
Dante, or whatever.

00:10:24.639 --> 00:10:29.558
He goes on thinking about these
concerns and how everything that

00:10:29.558 --> 00:10:34.009
belongs to the world of art is
the part of the path to the

00:10:34.009 --> 00:10:34.870
Divine.
 

00:10:34.870 --> 00:10:38.011
Theology and aesthetics not
just as--well,

00:10:38.011 --> 00:10:41.921
aesthetics as a way of making
beautiful the reality,

00:10:41.921 --> 00:10:45.370
the theological content of
Dante's faith.

00:10:45.370 --> 00:10:47.736
Not just that,
but--that's no longer the

00:10:47.736 --> 00:10:49.620
question of an ornamentation.
 

00:10:49.620 --> 00:10:52.643
That was the problem,
by the way, of Lucretius who at

00:10:52.643 --> 00:10:55.672
one point says,
I wanted to write poetry

00:10:55.672 --> 00:11:00.214
because I want to make pleasant
the bitter medicine that

00:11:00.214 --> 00:11:03.600
Epicurus goes on administering
to you.

00:11:03.600 --> 00:11:06.139
The way he says it,
that the gods have fled,

00:11:06.139 --> 00:11:09.506
that there is no such a thing
as sacredness in the cosmos,

00:11:09.506 --> 00:11:11.278
that's too bitter to bear.
 

00:11:11.278 --> 00:11:15.015
I'm going to say it nicely,
now that's really--not so for

00:11:15.015 --> 00:11:15.548
Dante.
 

00:11:15.548 --> 00:11:21.038
How the actual exercise of art,
it's an ascetic exercise.

00:11:21.038 --> 00:11:24.340
You move through art,
you refine, you think,

00:11:24.340 --> 00:11:26.950
and you question all the
things.

00:11:26.950 --> 00:11:29.923
It's not just an
ornamentation--ornamentation of

00:11:29.923 --> 00:11:33.654
being the word for cosmetics,
for beautifying that which one

00:11:33.654 --> 00:11:35.678
has--that which he will say.
 

00:11:35.678 --> 00:11:38.330
These were the concerns and we
came to Canto XXXIII of

00:11:38.330 --> 00:11:41.131
Paradise,
and I maintain to you and as

00:11:41.131 --> 00:11:44.846
way of recapitulation,
I think I have said to you,

00:11:44.846 --> 00:11:48.000
I hope that I have said it all
to you,

00:11:48.000 --> 00:11:54.544
but I will gladly go over it
and I hope that if you see more

00:11:54.544 --> 00:11:57.607
or not quite,
haven't seen what I think I've

00:11:57.607 --> 00:12:00.638
been saying,
say it, that's really your last

00:12:00.638 --> 00:12:04.399
chance as far as I go in this
public mode here.

00:12:04.399 --> 00:12:08.541
The first thing that we
understand about Dante's

00:12:08.541 --> 00:12:13.740
theology is the extraordinary
rootedness of this theology in

00:12:13.740 --> 00:12:15.678
the human reality.
 

00:12:15.678 --> 00:12:20.645
Canto XXXIII is the canto of
prayer, and we'll talk more

00:12:20.645 --> 00:12:24.710
about the prayer as a mode of
theologizing.

00:12:24.710 --> 00:12:26.850
Why is it a special mode of
theologizing?

00:12:26.850 --> 00:12:29.070
The first thing is that it is a
prayer to the Virgin Mary,

00:12:29.070 --> 00:12:33.506
that is to say a way of
thinking about how the Divine

00:12:33.506 --> 00:12:38.200
has entered the world of history
and the human flesh.

00:12:38.200 --> 00:12:41.360
There's no such thing as an
extraordinary--

00:12:41.360 --> 00:12:45.613
and I think--even talking about
the cosmology of Dante I tried

00:12:45.613 --> 00:12:48.190
to hint,
tried to say--look the physical

00:12:48.190 --> 00:12:51.870
world and the metaphysical world
are all part of one universe.

00:12:51.870 --> 00:12:54.788
They are two separate
hemispheres and yet there is

00:12:54.788 --> 00:12:57.394
always a cross,
there is a chiasmus that will

00:12:57.394 --> 00:12:59.917
connect them,
but will make them because

00:12:59.917 --> 00:13:02.308
that's the irony of every
chiasmus.

00:13:02.308 --> 00:13:03.700
You know what I mean by
chiasmus?

00:13:03.700 --> 00:13:06.808
It comes from the Greek letter
chi in Greek,

00:13:06.808 --> 00:13:09.373
that's a chiasmus,
an X, and wherever a chiasmus

00:13:09.373 --> 00:13:12.210
you have a point of intersection
of the two arms,

00:13:12.210 --> 00:13:14.548
but that becomes also a point
of flight.

00:13:14.548 --> 00:13:17.466
Things come together and can be
seen to come together,

00:13:17.466 --> 00:13:20.658
but things also seem to be
divergent, seem to be going away

00:13:20.658 --> 00:13:22.090
from each other,
okay.

00:13:22.090 --> 00:13:26.904
This is the cosmos of Dante;
it's an extension of what he

00:13:26.904 --> 00:13:29.070
will say in the prayer to the
Virgin.

00:13:29.070 --> 00:13:34.379
The human rootedness of the
Divine, not dualities,

00:13:34.379 --> 00:13:38.389
okay, that's really a primary
item.

00:13:38.389 --> 00:13:41.090
This will conclude,
with the idea that with the--

00:13:41.090 --> 00:13:45.706
and makes it persuasive that
what Dante sees and remembers at

00:13:45.706 --> 00:13:49.202
the end is our effigy,
which is clearly a throwback to

00:13:49.202 --> 00:13:49.658
Genesis.
 

00:13:49.658 --> 00:13:54.158
Let us make man in our image
and likeness,

00:13:54.158 --> 00:13:57.376
that's what Dante will see,
but this also means that we are

00:13:57.376 --> 00:14:00.376
in the world of images,
that Dante's own journey ends

00:14:00.376 --> 00:14:03.888
in the world of images,
but not in images as deceptive

00:14:03.888 --> 00:14:06.688
appearances,
only--that which we saw the

00:14:06.688 --> 00:14:09.340
whole of Purgatorio is
full of,

00:14:09.340 --> 00:14:12.649
now somehow the image probably
because of our,

00:14:12.649 --> 00:14:16.917
the shared quality of that
image becomes the locus

00:14:16.917 --> 00:14:18.668
of the Sacred itself.
 

00:14:18.668 --> 00:14:22.835
It becomes, not something that
just hides, but also reveals the

00:14:22.835 --> 00:14:23.440
Divine.
 

00:14:23.440 --> 00:14:26.732
The second thing that I think
that we have learned to

00:14:26.732 --> 00:14:30.090
understand about this theology
of Dante is freedom.

00:14:30.090 --> 00:14:34.298
That the foundation of Dante's
own--the foundation of his

00:14:34.298 --> 00:14:38.057
beliefs, the foundation of his
theological beliefs,

00:14:38.057 --> 00:14:39.408
is in freedom.
 

00:14:39.408 --> 00:14:41.759
We talked about the theological
virtues,

00:14:41.759 --> 00:14:44.912
as you recall,
the theological virtues faith,

00:14:44.912 --> 00:14:48.206
hope, and charity:
XXIV, XXV, and XXVI with the

00:14:48.206 --> 00:14:51.360
various examinations that Dante
goes on.

00:14:51.360 --> 00:14:55.774
If you recall,
we were talking about the fact

00:14:55.774 --> 00:15:00.788
that Dante thinks of faith as an
act of freedom.

00:15:00.788 --> 00:15:05.201
That's not unusual for those
who have any theological

00:15:05.201 --> 00:15:10.292
interest to even find traces and
implications of this kind of

00:15:10.292 --> 00:15:11.480
statement.
 

00:15:11.480 --> 00:15:15.240
Faith is, for Dante,
a way of knowing;

00:15:15.240 --> 00:15:18.999
he connects it with knowledge,
which is not just a way of

00:15:18.999 --> 00:15:22.759
saying that faith intervenes
when knowledge stops because

00:15:22.759 --> 00:15:26.720
someone who is interested in his
curiosity of knowing--

00:15:26.720 --> 00:15:29.169
now I don't know I'll try hard,
maybe tomorrow I will know,

00:15:29.169 --> 00:15:31.710
I don't need any faith, right?
 

00:15:31.710 --> 00:15:34.298
If you really think about the
relationship between knowledge

00:15:34.298 --> 00:15:36.471
and faith,
you can't say faith emerges at

00:15:36.471 --> 00:15:39.621
the boundary line of knowledge
because that boundary line is

00:15:39.621 --> 00:15:42.980
always shifting,
and that would imply the

00:15:42.980 --> 00:15:47.370
progressive reduction of a kind
of receding,

00:15:47.370 --> 00:15:54.250
and diminishing fragment of the
dimension of faith.

00:15:54.250 --> 00:15:57.831
Dante's saying by connecting a
university examination and the

00:15:57.831 --> 00:16:01.293
problem of faith is that faith
itself is a way of knowing I

00:16:01.293 --> 00:16:03.994
have faith,
and that means that I see the

00:16:03.994 --> 00:16:06.158
world in an entirely different
way;

00:16:06.158 --> 00:16:09.570
I can see myself disengaged
from everything around me.

00:16:09.570 --> 00:16:12.230
I can see that nothing really
matters;

00:16:12.230 --> 00:16:16.336
that all the patterns and
parameters of reasons are going

00:16:16.336 --> 00:16:17.950
to be found wanting.
 

00:16:17.950 --> 00:16:21.370
That's really--so it's tied
with freedom.

00:16:21.370 --> 00:16:25.668
Hope introduces the question of
the future, and you cannot have

00:16:25.668 --> 00:16:27.678
freedom without the future.
 

00:16:27.678 --> 00:16:30.690
We talked about these temporal
issues.

00:16:30.690 --> 00:16:33.634
You can only think about the
possibility of a future if you

00:16:33.634 --> 00:16:36.626
believe that it is a novelty,
if there is a freedom--if you

00:16:36.626 --> 00:16:38.889
are in bondage you cannot really
think of that.

00:16:38.889 --> 00:16:42.303
Theologically,
because I don't want to confuse

00:16:42.303 --> 00:16:46.857
you at all, you remember that
all three cantos were literally

00:16:46.857 --> 00:16:49.590
woven with references to Exodus.
 

00:16:49.590 --> 00:16:54.398
All three cantos and the story
of Exodus, which is crucial to

00:16:54.398 --> 00:16:58.645
Dante's poetic figuration,
is the story of the freedom

00:16:58.645 --> 00:17:00.889
from a state of bondage.
 

00:17:00.889 --> 00:17:04.990
This is the way we understand
him, but Dante also knows that

00:17:04.990 --> 00:17:09.440
freedom can--you only have to
shift--this is Luther of course;

00:17:09.440 --> 00:17:12.088
freedom and faith are one in
the same thing.

00:17:12.088 --> 00:17:13.910
In his attack--you remember
that?

00:17:13.910 --> 00:17:16.675
I mentioned this to you,
it doesn't concern Dante but

00:17:16.675 --> 00:17:19.548
concerns the issue and so we'll
mention for clarity.

00:17:19.548 --> 00:17:21.242
They debated,
the two of them,

00:17:21.242 --> 00:17:24.686
Luther and Erasmus over the
idea of what freedom of the will

00:17:24.686 --> 00:17:26.818
means,
and they are really debating a

00:17:26.818 --> 00:17:29.798
text written a century earlier
by one humanist by the name of

00:17:29.798 --> 00:17:32.480
Valla and they disagree about
what that text means.

00:17:32.480 --> 00:17:38.801
Luther says to Erasmus,
you really are interested in

00:17:38.801 --> 00:17:42.150
faith as a form of order.
 

00:17:42.150 --> 00:17:46.147
I'm interested in faith as a
form of freedom because that

00:17:46.147 --> 00:17:48.288
frees me from all loyalties.
 

00:17:48.288 --> 00:17:52.230
It's madness by the sublime
quality of the statement,

00:17:52.230 --> 00:17:55.929
but you only have to shift the
ground a little bit and realize

00:17:55.929 --> 00:17:58.441
that freedom,
can really become,

00:17:58.441 --> 00:18:01.009
and is the source of atheism.
 

00:18:01.009 --> 00:18:05.468
Atheism, all of a sudden,
becomes important because human

00:18:05.468 --> 00:18:09.210
beings don't want to be
subjected to anybody.

00:18:09.210 --> 00:18:12.258
It's part of the project to say
I am my own man,

00:18:12.258 --> 00:18:15.175
I am my own woman,
I want to do exactly what I

00:18:15.175 --> 00:18:15.759
want.
 

00:18:15.759 --> 00:18:20.111
I don't want to have any
loyalties or accept anything

00:18:20.111 --> 00:18:22.118
that I don't even see.
 

00:18:22.118 --> 00:18:27.230
We can bear with the master
that we see and maybe has a

00:18:27.230 --> 00:18:30.523
knife at us,
but someone as distant and

00:18:30.523 --> 00:18:33.893
remote we--
Dante then says that's the

00:18:33.893 --> 00:18:38.420
peculiarity of this religious
belief of mine,

00:18:38.420 --> 00:18:43.086
which is really all about
freedom, including the freedom

00:18:43.086 --> 00:18:45.038
to deny the divinity.
 

00:18:45.038 --> 00:18:47.772
This is extraordinary,
never heard of in the history

00:18:47.772 --> 00:18:51.150
of--as far as I know and I have
a very limited knowledge believe

00:18:51.150 --> 00:18:54.178
me, it's no rhetoric;
very limited knowledge but I

00:18:54.178 --> 00:18:56.348
have never seen anything like
this.

00:18:56.348 --> 00:19:00.563
The third element about this
theology is really the great

00:19:00.563 --> 00:19:03.798
element of love,
to discover that the way to

00:19:03.798 --> 00:19:07.371
God, yes it's hard;
there are many ways first of

00:19:07.371 --> 00:19:08.160
all to God.
 

00:19:08.160 --> 00:19:11.511
There is the philosophical of
going through knowing,

00:19:11.511 --> 00:19:14.666
there is the linguistic way
through the language,

00:19:14.666 --> 00:19:17.558
and I'll come to this issue in
a moment.

00:19:17.558 --> 00:19:20.419
There is poetry,
there is the world of beauty,

00:19:20.419 --> 00:19:24.105
then there's the language of
the heart, but primarily it is

00:19:24.105 --> 00:19:26.328
the path to the Divine is love.
 

00:19:26.328 --> 00:19:30.423
Dante understands,
I wasn't saying that love is so

00:19:30.423 --> 00:19:35.186
mysterious because I know that
deep down you are all young

00:19:35.186 --> 00:19:37.346
people,
many of you are,

00:19:37.346 --> 00:19:41.108
a couple here are younger,
much younger than I am but not

00:19:41.108 --> 00:19:43.699
really that young,
so they are not surprised by

00:19:43.699 --> 00:19:44.210
any this.
 

00:19:44.210 --> 00:19:47.108
But I know that deep down,
I remember being young,

00:19:47.108 --> 00:19:49.170
how I think about the mystery
of love,

00:19:49.170 --> 00:19:51.980
ah… that really speaks
to everybody's heart.

00:19:51.980 --> 00:19:53.480
I wasn't meaning it that way.
 

00:19:53.480 --> 00:19:57.674
It is really a thought point
that the principle of election,

00:19:57.674 --> 00:20:01.443
which is so crucial to love,
it really cannot be quite

00:20:01.443 --> 00:20:02.440
explained.
 

00:20:02.440 --> 00:20:06.108
I really was meaning it in this
theological way as possible.

00:20:06.108 --> 00:20:09.703
I was already thinking about
the statements that I was going

00:20:09.703 --> 00:20:12.078
to make today about Dante's
theology.

00:20:12.078 --> 00:20:15.230
These are some of the issues
that Dante has.

00:20:15.230 --> 00:20:18.905
The other day,
yesterday, the day before I was

00:20:18.905 --> 00:20:23.890
asked the question about one
line in Dante and I was very--

00:20:23.890 --> 00:20:26.919
it was a very good question
about the fact that Dante's

00:20:26.919 --> 00:20:30.141
allowed to see the truth,
that the light he saw was the

00:20:30.141 --> 00:20:30.539
truth.
 

00:20:30.539 --> 00:20:31.950
That was a very good question.
 

00:20:31.950 --> 00:20:33.640
What does it mean?
 

00:20:33.640 --> 00:20:36.256
To me it was so clear,
and I apologize,

00:20:36.256 --> 00:20:40.317
because I said well this is
really the biblical idea in your

00:20:40.317 --> 00:20:43.210
light, which your notes will
tell you.

00:20:43.210 --> 00:20:46.551
In your light I see the light,
we see the light,

00:20:46.551 --> 00:20:48.259
and what does it mean?
 

00:20:48.259 --> 00:20:49.910
In your light we see the light.
 

00:20:49.910 --> 00:20:54.838
What it is that it's part of
this mystery that if you are a

00:20:54.838 --> 00:20:59.855
mystic and you think that the
Divine is wrapped in a kind of

00:20:59.855 --> 00:21:03.778
transcendent darkness,
that's the language,

00:21:03.778 --> 00:21:08.420
or that it is really all
wrapped in impenetrable light,

00:21:08.420 --> 00:21:11.887
it's both the same because
neither light has the

00:21:11.887 --> 00:21:16.390
peculiarity never letting you
see the origin of the light,

00:21:16.390 --> 00:21:19.674
and darkness has the
peculiarity of never letting you

00:21:19.674 --> 00:21:21.759
see the origin of the darkness.
 

00:21:21.759 --> 00:21:24.238
When Dante reaches
Paradiso XXXIII,

00:21:24.238 --> 00:21:27.319
and that's the meaning your
light, we see the light,

00:21:27.319 --> 00:21:29.920
Dante sees finally the origin
of light.

00:21:29.920 --> 00:21:31.930
That's the point.
 

00:21:31.930 --> 00:21:36.074
There are moments where his
sight can become so incredibly

00:21:36.074 --> 00:21:40.000
sharp and so penetrating,
so look at all these ways.

00:21:40.000 --> 00:21:43.344
The ways--there are many ways
in which we can take available

00:21:43.344 --> 00:21:46.404
to us and it seems that we are
always stumbling against

00:21:46.404 --> 00:21:49.410
something that in the long run
you have to stop,

00:21:49.410 --> 00:21:54.682
and yet if you love,
if you think that beauty is

00:21:54.682 --> 00:21:57.145
part--
which is part of love,

00:21:57.145 --> 00:22:00.955
beauty is part of--
love is the hunger for beauty

00:22:00.955 --> 00:22:03.259
the neo-Platonist will say.
 

00:22:03.259 --> 00:22:07.162
In the Florentine neo-Platonist
Lorenzo--I don't know where he

00:22:07.162 --> 00:22:12.028
found it probably in Plotinus;
love is the hunger for beauty.

00:22:12.028 --> 00:22:15.659
All of these are ways that
Dante keeps opening for us in

00:22:15.659 --> 00:22:19.221
our journey to the Divine,
and then there is the prayer

00:22:19.221 --> 00:22:21.730
which is the question of
language.

00:22:21.730 --> 00:22:27.261
That has also become one of the
ways in which I indicate that

00:22:27.261 --> 00:22:32.608
there is a theological root to
the question of language.

00:22:32.608 --> 00:22:37.682
Not only that we speak out of
speaking and language is an

00:22:37.682 --> 00:22:41.627
allegory,
a parable of our desires,

00:22:41.627 --> 00:22:46.818
a parable of what we lack,
we speak because we don't have.

00:22:46.818 --> 00:22:51.273
That's the specific--and we
speak because we--the seat mate

00:22:51.273 --> 00:22:55.498
and we are pointing maybe
without really knowing to what

00:22:55.498 --> 00:22:56.420
we need.
 

00:22:56.420 --> 00:22:57.960
It's always a question of need.
 

00:22:57.960 --> 00:23:01.579
Dante has always had a way of
connecting language and desire,

00:23:01.579 --> 00:23:04.295
we talked about that,
that's one the themes we

00:23:04.295 --> 00:23:05.140
discussed.
 

00:23:05.140 --> 00:23:08.165
Then all of a sudden in
Paradiso XXXIII,

00:23:08.165 --> 00:23:11.720
though I said to you,
look the language now changes.

00:23:11.720 --> 00:23:16.171
First of all,
the prayer to the Virgin is all

00:23:16.171 --> 00:23:20.520
about longing,
this state of longing but not

00:23:20.520 --> 00:23:22.140
languishing.
 

00:23:22.140 --> 00:23:25.202
There is an etymological
connection there somewhere which

00:23:25.202 --> 00:23:27.432
is not--
I'm not going to get into but

00:23:27.432 --> 00:23:30.912
there's a longing for the Divine
to show itself to Bernard of

00:23:30.912 --> 00:23:32.710
Clairvaux, the great mystic.
 

00:23:32.710 --> 00:23:37.130
He who is the great fierce
opponent of Abelard,

00:23:37.130 --> 00:23:39.190
appears on the scene and
therefore they--

00:23:39.190 --> 00:23:42.240
you can overhear the polemics
which we haven't got time for,

00:23:42.240 --> 00:23:45.631
the polemics between Abelard
and Bernard that are clearly

00:23:45.631 --> 00:23:48.660
behind his apparition in
Paradiso XXXIII.

00:23:48.660 --> 00:23:52.490
They all are waiting for the
Divine to show itself forth,

00:23:52.490 --> 00:23:57.242
right, and this language--and
yet this desire all of a sudden

00:23:57.242 --> 00:24:00.730
becomes the language of joy,
of enjoyment.

00:24:00.730 --> 00:24:04.059
That's such an extraordinary
shift.

00:24:04.059 --> 00:24:05.480
Why?
 

00:24:05.480 --> 00:24:10.088
Because Dante understands the
problem with desire;

00:24:10.088 --> 00:24:15.318
of course, we like to--we're
always talking about how much--

00:24:15.318 --> 00:24:19.119
how permanent we like to be,
in a state of permanent desires

00:24:19.119 --> 00:24:21.890
because that's what makes us
feel alive,

00:24:21.890 --> 00:24:25.480
young, to desire,
you want something.

00:24:25.480 --> 00:24:32.618
It's true, it's part of the
great power of desire,

00:24:32.618 --> 00:24:37.281
and the language of desire,
but if desire were without an

00:24:37.281 --> 00:24:42.277
object ever then desire becomes
of the greatest absurdity and

00:24:42.277 --> 00:24:43.358
futility.
 

00:24:43.358 --> 00:24:47.383
If we go around thinking that
we are in a labyrinth of desires

00:24:47.383 --> 00:24:51.210
then really that is--it's a
joke, desire becomes a joke.

00:24:51.210 --> 00:24:55.276
Dante places this idea of
enjoyment, the possibility of

00:24:55.276 --> 00:24:58.589
this sweetness that instills in
his heart.

00:24:58.589 --> 00:24:59.910
These are the issues.
 

00:24:59.910 --> 00:25:02.209
Then finally,
this idea of prayer,

00:25:02.209 --> 00:25:04.088
and I want to stop there.
 

00:25:04.088 --> 00:25:08.150
Let me stop with the question
of prayer and then get your

00:25:08.150 --> 00:25:09.019
questions.
 

00:25:09.019 --> 00:25:13.183
The whole poem,
I think, from the perspective

00:25:13.183 --> 00:25:17.943
of Paradiso XXXIII,
taking retrospectively the

00:25:17.943 --> 00:25:22.205
view, not only the fact that
there are references to the

00:25:22.205 --> 00:25:26.700
first words Dante uses in
Inferno I is a prayer.

00:25:26.700 --> 00:25:28.526
"Miserere di
me,"

00:25:28.526 --> 00:25:31.680
"Have mercy on me,"
he doesn't even know whether

00:25:31.680 --> 00:25:34.271
you are a shade or a man,
he sees something,

00:25:34.271 --> 00:25:36.749
a shape indistinct,
turns out to be Virgil,

00:25:36.749 --> 00:25:38.200
turns out to be poetry.
 

00:25:38.200 --> 00:25:42.355
This is the poetry that lends
itself, offers itself completely

00:25:42.355 --> 00:25:42.970
freely.
 

00:25:42.970 --> 00:25:45.548
You can go to the library and
pick up a book,

00:25:45.548 --> 00:25:47.541
a free act of someone's
generosity.

00:25:47.541 --> 00:25:48.480
There it is.
 

00:25:48.480 --> 00:25:50.818
He turns to it and begins with
a prayer,

00:25:50.818 --> 00:25:54.410
and the poem ends with a
prayer, and ends with--

00:25:54.410 --> 00:25:56.460
it begins with a prayer--the
whole poem,

00:25:56.460 --> 00:26:00.950
the real quality and nature of
language is to be a prayer.

00:26:00.950 --> 00:26:05.876
A prayer implying the tension
that we have all the time told

00:26:05.876 --> 00:26:08.965
what, for Dante,
told what necessarily

00:26:08.965 --> 00:26:10.470
transcends us.
 

00:26:10.470 --> 00:26:17.157
There's always a reality that
is touched directly by the hand

00:26:17.157 --> 00:26:22.509
of God, but escapes the world of
the human plans,

00:26:22.509 --> 00:26:25.519
and the human projects.
 

00:26:25.519 --> 00:26:30.208
This is what I think the whole
poem is about,

00:26:30.208 --> 00:26:35.429
and it's above all a poem
addressed to the future,

00:26:35.429 --> 00:26:37.558
addressed to us.
 

00:26:37.558 --> 00:26:39.980
That is to say,
it's not a poem about the past,

00:26:39.980 --> 00:26:42.710
Dante is the least nostalgic of
poets,

00:26:42.710 --> 00:26:45.224
it's so easy,
if you really go wherever and

00:26:45.224 --> 00:26:47.920
you tell your grandchildren you
read Dante.

00:26:47.920 --> 00:26:50.154
I thought that Dante is a nice
little story about the Middle

00:26:50.154 --> 00:26:51.981
Ages;
we are all nostalgic about the

00:26:51.981 --> 00:26:52.660
Middle Ages.
 

00:26:52.660 --> 00:26:54.875
Maybe some of you are here--how
were these guys,

00:26:54.875 --> 00:26:55.960
how were they living?
 

00:26:55.960 --> 00:26:58.950
In a world of absolute
certainties, right?

00:26:58.950 --> 00:27:05.538
Dante is the poet of openness,
the poet who understands

00:27:05.538 --> 00:27:09.808
reason, and understands the
risk.

00:27:09.808 --> 00:27:12.828
Now, that's really what this
poem is about,

00:27:12.828 --> 00:27:15.509
a poem about the future,
the poem addressed with a

00:27:15.509 --> 00:27:17.480
number of apostrophes to
readers,

00:27:17.480 --> 00:27:19.632
and whenever you read
apostrophe to readers from

00:27:19.632 --> 00:27:22.380
beginning of Inferno to
roughly Paradiso X,

00:27:22.380 --> 00:27:24.690
every so often Dante addresses
us.

00:27:24.690 --> 00:27:26.898
You remember I said,
at one point he stops,

00:27:26.898 --> 00:27:29.317
he made this point,
what are these addresses to

00:27:29.317 --> 00:27:29.950
readers?
 

00:27:29.950 --> 00:27:31.788
We can read it--whenever you
have a kind of--

00:27:31.788 --> 00:27:34.519
up to the eighteenth century
you always read novels,

00:27:34.519 --> 00:27:37.440
now my dear reader,
now my gentle reader,

00:27:37.440 --> 00:27:38.880
they are coaxing you,
pretending they're coaxing you,

00:27:38.880 --> 00:27:42.458
they couldn't care whether you
read it or not I don't think

00:27:42.458 --> 00:27:43.259
ultimately.
 

00:27:43.259 --> 00:27:45.519
Dante doesn't really care
whether we are reading him or

00:27:45.519 --> 00:27:45.769
not.
 

00:27:45.769 --> 00:27:49.817
Now you're following the little
shape of poetry,

00:27:49.817 --> 00:27:53.178
the few of you,
and I think he means it,

00:27:53.178 --> 00:27:57.400
who are not afraid of how rough
the seas are.

00:27:57.400 --> 00:27:59.680
You could shipwreck and all of
that--

00:27:59.680 --> 00:28:04.190
of course you could read those
apostrophes as a way of saying,

00:28:04.190 --> 00:28:08.278
look I need you readers because
if I have readers I'm

00:28:08.278 --> 00:28:11.190
constituting myself into an
author.

00:28:11.190 --> 00:28:15.670
The measure in which there are
readers, then I am the author,

00:28:15.670 --> 00:28:19.777
