00:47:20.489 --> 00:47:22.851
the end where there is
plentitude it seems to be a

00:47:22.851 --> 00:47:25.260
completely transformed
understanding of love,

00:47:25.260 --> 00:47:28.539
that it's not possible to
go--to return from in the

00:47:28.539 --> 00:47:29.719
beatific vision.
 

00:47:29.719 --> 00:47:32.532
If you have this plentitude,
is it possible to go back

00:47:32.532 --> 00:47:35.398
because it does seem like it's a
completely transformed

00:47:35.398 --> 00:47:38.688
understanding of love when you
have just the plentitude and not

00:47:38.688 --> 00:47:40.969
lack anymore so with that mind
does--

00:47:40.969 --> 00:47:44.036
is Dante ever able to attain
this love because this love that

00:47:44.036 --> 00:47:47.257
does have plentitude seems like
it should end in silence with no

00:47:47.257 --> 00:47:49.659
language and Dante does go back
and speak,

00:47:49.659 --> 00:47:53.596
and he does--he is still--he is
a pilgrim and a poet and so does

00:47:53.596 --> 00:47:57.157
he really ever move from the
images to the essences and is

00:47:57.157 --> 00:48:00.844
the uncertainty at the end not
just because we have to go on

00:48:00.844 --> 00:48:04.969
the journey our self but because
he is still on the journey?

00:48:04.969 --> 00:48:12.724
Prof: Well,
you are really voicing a very

00:48:12.724 --> 00:48:17.510
delicate issue in the poem.
 

00:48:17.510 --> 00:48:23.835
It's a very controversial issue
because that also implies the

00:48:23.835 --> 00:48:26.050
status of the poem.
 

00:48:26.050 --> 00:48:27.699
Do you understand what I'm
saying?

00:48:27.699 --> 00:48:30.927
In other words,
if you really think that Dante

00:48:30.927 --> 00:48:33.277
has seen--
has had a beatific vision and

00:48:33.277 --> 00:48:36.338
he has,
and now he's writing the poem

00:48:36.338 --> 00:48:39.974
to tell us about it,
then you're really saying that

00:48:39.974 --> 00:48:42.972
the poem itself belongs to a
higher level of experience

00:48:42.972 --> 00:48:46.248
because it's written by someone
who is in full possession of

00:48:46.248 --> 00:48:46.860
grace.
 

00:48:46.860 --> 00:48:48.429
That's your point, right?
 

00:48:48.429 --> 00:48:52.867
That's a very delicate point
because I have not been teaching

00:48:52.867 --> 00:48:55.530
Dante that way,
right, I have not.

00:48:55.530 --> 00:48:58.599
We are right to say this,
at the moment of

00:48:58.599 --> 00:49:02.043
recapitulation,
I probably would--I have wasted

00:49:02.043 --> 00:49:03.840
your time all along.
 

00:49:03.840 --> 00:49:07.380
One little detail that I want
to bring to your attention and

00:49:07.380 --> 00:49:10.079
then I will go to the more
general problem;

00:49:10.079 --> 00:49:13.920
when Dante meets Beatrice in
Purgatorio XXXI,

00:49:13.920 --> 00:49:16.219
this is getting really to be a
recapitulation,

00:49:16.219 --> 00:49:18.219
we're talking about everything
in the poem now,

00:49:18.219 --> 00:49:21.820
he meets Beatrice in
Purgatorio XXX and then

00:49:21.820 --> 00:49:22.539
in XXXI.
 

00:49:22.539 --> 00:49:26.275
In Purgatorio XXXI
Beatrice forces Dante to go into

00:49:26.275 --> 00:49:27.260
a confession.
 

00:49:27.260 --> 00:49:31.059
You have to go into an
admission of who you are,

00:49:31.059 --> 00:49:34.990
and has to be public;
cannot say I know you know,

00:49:34.990 --> 00:49:39.594
but you have to be duly ashamed
because only that way you can

00:49:39.594 --> 00:49:43.659
transcend whatever it is that
you have within you.

00:49:43.659 --> 00:49:49.634
Dante reluctantly will agree to
do that and then Beatrice will

00:49:49.634 --> 00:49:52.594
say,
I want you to go through this

00:49:52.594 --> 00:49:56.003
so that another time,
the future tense,

00:49:56.003 --> 00:50:00.465
when you will see,
will meet the siren I want you

00:50:00.465 --> 00:50:01.840
to be stronger.
 

00:50:01.840 --> 00:50:05.797
This to me implies,
that's one of the many--Dante

00:50:05.797 --> 00:50:09.510
sees Casella,
another aesthetic temptation.

00:50:09.510 --> 00:50:12.070
One doesn't have to have the
temptation to kill someone,

00:50:12.070 --> 00:50:16.097
to really feel that what is
out--has fallen out of grace but

00:50:16.097 --> 00:50:18.920
this is--
he meets Casella and he

00:50:18.920 --> 00:50:24.139
remembers how sweet was that
song he heard from Casella and

00:50:24.139 --> 00:50:28.010
that sweetness still resounds
within me.

00:50:28.010 --> 00:50:33.077
Now Dante is writing--is
talking as a poet--he meets

00:50:33.077 --> 00:50:37.250
Ulysses, I grieve then and I
grieve now.

00:50:37.250 --> 00:50:43.402
There is a way in which states
within the pilgrim do not really

00:50:43.402 --> 00:50:46.335
go on changing;
they are the same,

00:50:46.335 --> 00:50:50.005
implying that there is some
kind of continuity between

00:50:50.005 --> 00:50:52.289
pilgrimage and poetry writing.
 

00:50:52.289 --> 00:50:57.519
To me, the writing of poetry is
an extension of the pilgrimage.

00:50:57.519 --> 00:51:02.429
Dante though goes on saying;
I have had the beatific vision.

00:51:02.429 --> 00:51:05.940
I am now--I know what enjoyment
means,

00:51:05.940 --> 00:51:09.039
not just desire,
but I'm coming back to the

00:51:09.039 --> 00:51:12.951
Earth and therefore I cannot
come back to the Earth as

00:51:12.951 --> 00:51:17.010
anything less than a human being
with one project,

00:51:17.010 --> 00:51:21.244
the project to write a poem,
because I want to retrieve that

00:51:21.244 --> 00:51:24.329
joy and because I want to share
that joy.

00:51:24.329 --> 00:51:27.500
So I have set down two things
in my answer to you.

00:51:27.500 --> 00:51:31.896
One talking about the question
of the pilgrim's experience and

00:51:31.896 --> 00:51:35.501
the relationship of the
pilgrim's experience to the

00:51:35.501 --> 00:51:40.496
writing of a poem,
but I have also said that the

00:51:40.496 --> 00:51:43.949
poem stands as a sign for us.
 

00:51:43.949 --> 00:51:49.646
A hermeneutical moment;
Dante means it for us so that

00:51:49.646 --> 00:51:52.690
we can--his journey continues.
 

00:51:52.690 --> 00:51:55.789
That's my answer.
 

00:51:55.789 --> 00:51:59.018
You don't have to agree with it
because there are--

00:51:59.018 --> 00:52:02.480
I know there is--there are
other people,

00:52:02.480 --> 00:52:05.632
I have been fighting those
people for a long time in my

00:52:05.632 --> 00:52:07.608
life,
I don't want to go back to

00:52:07.608 --> 00:52:10.351
those fights,
but I think that that this my

00:52:10.351 --> 00:52:12.159
way of looking at it,
okay.

00:52:12.159 --> 00:52:13.679
I can give you more
bibliography;

00:52:13.679 --> 00:52:16.599
I would rather not actually,
to tell you the truth.

00:52:16.599 --> 00:52:19.012
I don't want to tell you about
those people who are writing the

00:52:19.012 --> 00:52:19.480
other way.
 

00:52:19.480 --> 00:52:23.780
I have written about them in my
books.

00:52:33.030 --> 00:52:34.922
Student:  I was
wondering if you could talk a

00:52:34.922 --> 00:52:37.000
little bit more about how Dante
views other religions.

00:52:37.000 --> 00:52:40.664
In particular,
Judaism and if it sort of falls

00:52:40.664 --> 00:52:44.409
underneath his idea of religion
as freedom,

00:52:44.409 --> 00:52:48.269
and that if you have the
freedom to become an atheist you

00:52:48.269 --> 00:52:52.476
also have the freedom to choose
a different religion and if he

00:52:52.476 --> 00:52:56.474
views Judaism and Christianity
as sort of a continuity both

00:52:56.474 --> 00:53:00.405
deriving from the same basis or
if he ascribes the idea of

00:53:00.405 --> 00:53:04.197
secessionism that Christianity
has succeeded Judaism and

00:53:04.197 --> 00:53:07.376
invalidates it,
and for that reason we don't

00:53:07.376 --> 00:53:10.710
find, from what I can remember,
and Jews in Paradise.

00:53:10.710 --> 00:53:12.159
Prof: Oh yes you do.
 

00:53:12.159 --> 00:53:12.989
Student:  You do?
 

00:53:12.989 --> 00:53:13.639
Okay then that's my fault.
 

00:53:13.639 --> 00:53:15.793
Prof: Well,
now I have to correct you

00:53:15.793 --> 00:53:17.820
immediately because then maybe
you rephrase it--

00:53:17.820 --> 00:53:20.007
stay there--because you
probably will rephrase the

00:53:20.007 --> 00:53:20.500
question.
 

00:53:20.500 --> 00:53:26.425
When Dante goes on listing,
in the mystical rose,

00:53:26.425 --> 00:53:32.969
we even are told that Beatrice
sits next to Rachel.

00:53:32.969 --> 00:53:38.128
She has a way of elevating her
and then he goes on describing

00:53:38.128 --> 00:53:42.942
all the other--we talked at
length about Solomon who is a

00:53:42.942 --> 00:53:44.920
Jew, I think right?
 

00:53:44.920 --> 00:53:46.679
He was a Jew in the Bible.
 

00:53:46.679 --> 00:53:51.226
We went on talking about
Nathan, I tried to make light of

00:53:51.226 --> 00:53:56.259
it because I wanted to tell you
that Dante saw his own name but

00:53:56.259 --> 00:53:59.050
it's Nathan,
a prophet of David,

00:53:59.050 --> 00:54:03.730
and also in the harrowing of
hell which is Inferno IV,

00:54:03.730 --> 00:54:07.539
where Dante describes what
happens to Jesus after his

00:54:07.539 --> 00:54:09.780
death,
what does he do?

00:54:09.780 --> 00:54:11.570
He harrows hell.
 

00:54:11.570 --> 00:54:12.369
He goes into hell.
 

00:54:12.369 --> 00:54:13.739
What is he doing in hell?
 

00:54:13.739 --> 00:54:16.719
He goes there to take the
patriarchs and the women of

00:54:16.719 --> 00:54:18.610
Israel and take them to heaven.
 

00:54:18.610 --> 00:54:22.255
That's--these are facts--you
want to change your question or

00:54:22.255 --> 00:54:25.963
I can go on telling you more and
answering the real questions

00:54:25.963 --> 00:54:29.505
that you are raising,
that is to say the relationship

00:54:29.505 --> 00:54:33.130
between Christianity and Judaism
and the other religions.

00:54:33.130 --> 00:54:34.980
You want me to talk about that?
 

00:54:34.980 --> 00:54:37.295
Student:  That's
definitely the issue that I

00:54:37.295 --> 00:54:37.619
have.
 

00:54:37.619 --> 00:54:38.989
Whether Dante--I guess like I
said before,

00:54:38.989 --> 00:54:43.275
I guess by having Jews in
Paradise and having the

00:54:43.275 --> 00:54:47.559
figure of Christ come in and
collect the patriarchs,

00:54:47.559 --> 00:54:52.114
if he's trying to integrate
Judaism within Christianity or

00:54:52.114 --> 00:54:55.309
somehow to find a way between
the two?

00:54:55.309 --> 00:54:56.402
Prof: Yes.
 

00:54:56.402 --> 00:55:00.195
That is--so you're interested
especially about Dante's sense

00:55:00.195 --> 00:55:03.860
of--the relationship between
Christianity and Judaism?

00:55:03.860 --> 00:55:07.338
Do you want me to also address
the other issue of the way he

00:55:07.338 --> 00:55:09.579
looks at the Hindus and the
Muslims?

00:55:09.579 --> 00:55:12.469
We talked about Dante and the
other religions.

00:55:12.469 --> 00:55:15.740
In fact, when I--when we talked
about Dante's relationship with

00:55:15.740 --> 00:55:18.380
a sense of Christianity to the
other religions,

00:55:18.380 --> 00:55:22.300
I never mentioned the Jews and
probably that to you may have

00:55:22.300 --> 00:55:24.559
been a kind of glaring omission.
 

00:55:24.559 --> 00:55:27.202
This guy is talking about the
big religions,

00:55:27.202 --> 00:55:29.969
what about the matriarchs of
the religions?

00:55:29.969 --> 00:55:34.202
The Judaism--it's likely--I
occasionally thought maybe I

00:55:34.202 --> 00:55:37.391
should say something,
and then I said no because

00:55:37.391 --> 00:55:39.820
Dante doesn't talk about it and
so I wouldn't.

00:55:39.820 --> 00:55:44.949
Dante does talk when he
has--and he is not the only one,

00:55:44.949 --> 00:55:48.920
centuries before him they were
talking--

00:55:48.920 --> 00:55:54.480
a man like--a great theologian
by the name of Bonaventure,

00:55:54.480 --> 00:55:56.960
a professor of theology at the
University of Paris.

00:55:56.960 --> 00:56:03.217
I mentioned that text I'm sure,
and the year 1274 which is also

00:56:03.217 --> 00:56:07.389
the year of his death,
he was invited to Paris,

00:56:07.389 --> 00:56:10.065
he was teaching there,
because he was invited to

00:56:10.065 --> 00:56:12.489
deliver a number of lectures and
he gives these lectures,

00:56:12.489 --> 00:56:16.920
and then he goes on talking
about the other religions,

00:56:16.920 --> 00:56:22.409
the religions he knows:
Hindu and the Muslim religion.

00:56:22.409 --> 00:56:26.621
It's an argument--I mention
that because it seems to me that

00:56:26.621 --> 00:56:31.190
Dante follows Bonaventure fairly
closely when in the canto of St.

00:56:31.190 --> 00:56:34.402
Francis, Canto X,
the description of the--that

00:56:34.402 --> 00:56:35.331
legend of St.
 

00:56:35.331 --> 00:56:39.400
Francis, Francis is said to
have gone to the sultan to try

00:56:39.400 --> 00:56:45.347
to convert him and fails,
and then Dante also talks of

00:56:45.347 --> 00:56:49.237
the Hindus,
with the reference to the

00:56:49.237 --> 00:56:49.969
Ganges.
 

00:56:49.969 --> 00:56:53.449
When talking about justice,
Dante is talking about Europe,

00:56:53.449 --> 00:56:57.282
but in between he alludes to
the--he talks about the Persians

00:56:57.282 --> 00:57:00.434
and the Hindu,
the guy from the Hin who is

00:57:00.434 --> 00:57:04.019
born on the river Hindus,
he says you are of the Hindus.

00:57:04.019 --> 00:57:07.510
What is the conception there?
 

00:57:07.510 --> 00:57:10.434
The critique,
they are talking as Christians

00:57:10.434 --> 00:57:14.650
and they are talking from the
point of view of Christianity.

00:57:14.650 --> 00:57:19.440
The position that Bonaventure
will have, and Dante I think

00:57:19.440 --> 00:57:22.130
follows him, is the following.
 

00:57:22.130 --> 00:57:26.079
How does it--how it can be--can
they be distinguished?

00:57:26.079 --> 00:57:27.409
What do they share?
 

00:57:27.409 --> 00:57:29.039
They talk about what they share.
 

00:57:29.039 --> 00:57:30.730
What do they have in common?
 

00:57:30.730 --> 00:57:35.860
They have in common,
especially with the case of the

00:57:35.860 --> 00:57:40.489
Muslims, the biblical--the
Jewish tradition.

00:57:40.489 --> 00:57:44.393
Let me just not mince words
here, the Jewish tradition,

00:57:44.393 --> 00:57:47.429
that's really the common matrix
for him.

00:57:47.429 --> 00:57:51.679
He also notices differences,
that for instance,

00:57:51.679 --> 00:57:56.300
the theology of the Hindus is
one that presumes the

00:57:56.300 --> 00:58:00.090
diffusiveness of God into all
things.

00:58:00.090 --> 00:58:04.539
That's not--I don't think
that's something that unusual.

00:58:04.539 --> 00:58:06.000
What does it imply?
 

00:58:06.000 --> 00:58:10.878
Because they become critical of
it, it then implies the

00:58:10.878 --> 00:58:16.300
difficulty of making judgments
about what's good and evil.

00:58:16.300 --> 00:58:20.518
If God is everywhere you have
to--the sacrality of all things,

00:58:20.518 --> 00:58:23.228
which is a great idea,
and yet there are some aspects

00:58:23.228 --> 00:58:26.197
of reality where you don't like
to think that they are all

00:58:26.197 --> 00:58:26.719
alike.
 

00:58:26.719 --> 00:58:31.380
There is a way in which--this
is pantheism and can become--

00:58:31.380 --> 00:58:36.027
therefore can become--can be
critiqued as the lack of

00:58:36.027 --> 00:58:40.050
distinctions and hierarchies,
and ordering.

00:58:40.050 --> 00:58:44.422
When they come to the Muslims,
since the Muslim religion is

00:58:44.422 --> 00:58:48.570
one that talks about the
absolute impenetrability of the

00:58:48.570 --> 00:58:52.869
human mind cannot ever hope to
understand the Divine.

00:58:52.869 --> 00:58:57.726
We are here at the mercy of God
and we live only by the mercy of

00:58:57.726 --> 00:58:58.190
God.
 

00:58:58.190 --> 00:59:01.597
We cannot go on and say,
but I live by reason and I die

00:59:01.597 --> 00:59:04.059
by reason, and I can get to know
God.

00:59:04.059 --> 00:59:07.873
There is a great distance
between the human and the

00:59:07.873 --> 00:59:08.559
Divine.
 

00:59:08.559 --> 00:59:10.230
That's the critique.
 

00:59:10.230 --> 00:59:13.650
If this is true then we have
nothing to--

00:59:13.650 --> 00:59:16.387
there is an absolute
transcendence and he sees

00:59:16.387 --> 00:59:19.793
Christianity as that which
literally mediates between the

00:59:19.793 --> 00:59:22.896
two because there is that
transcendence and absolute

00:59:22.896 --> 00:59:26.601
transcendence of God,
the way the Muslims understand

00:59:26.601 --> 00:59:30.070
it, but there is also a
possibility of a mediation.

00:59:30.070 --> 00:59:33.010
Not total mediation the way the
Hindus understand it,

00:59:33.010 --> 00:59:35.894
but the mediation of the cross,
the mediation of the

00:59:35.894 --> 00:59:36.800
incarnation.
 

00:59:36.800 --> 00:59:39.219
This is the way Dante takes the
other religions.

00:59:39.219 --> 00:59:42.268
When it comes to the pagan
religions,

00:59:42.268 --> 00:59:45.768
not because they are the pagan
religions for instance,

00:59:45.768 --> 00:59:51.320
and Dante there follows very
much the pagan religion,

00:59:51.320 --> 00:59:53.768
the religion of the Greeks,
the religion of the Romans.

00:59:53.768 --> 00:59:55.793
Dante follows very much St.
 

00:59:55.793 --> 00:59:59.989
Augustine, who is the one who
talks at length about these

00:59:59.989 --> 01:00:00.739
issues.
 

01:00:00.739 --> 01:00:06.079
That's the ambiguity;
there are adumbrations of the

01:00:06.079 --> 01:00:10.641
Divine, but at the same time,
they can become also

01:00:10.641 --> 01:00:14.739
blasphemous idols of the
infernal powers.

01:00:14.739 --> 01:00:17.755
There is this way of really the
smashing, if you wish,

01:00:17.755 --> 01:00:18.610
of the idols.
 

01:00:18.610 --> 01:00:22.757
When it comes to Judaism,
which is really the question

01:00:22.757 --> 01:00:25.889
that--with which you started
actually.

01:00:25.889 --> 01:00:31.889
I think that Dante is--I talked
about that.

01:00:31.889 --> 01:00:33.579
I shouldn't say that I didn't
talk about it.

01:00:33.579 --> 01:00:39.059
You may recall that I made a
point in--

01:00:39.059 --> 01:00:42.690
at the beginning of the
readings of the poem,

01:00:42.690 --> 01:00:47.550
maybe I was not--it didn't seem
to be very important,

01:00:47.550 --> 01:00:51.469
it was important to me;
I sort of went on talking a

01:00:51.469 --> 01:00:56.210
little bit at length about the
question of birth.

01:00:56.210 --> 01:01:00.829
You remember how there are some
characters, representations,

01:01:00.829 --> 01:01:02.159
all characters?
 

01:01:02.159 --> 01:01:04.329
Dante continues,
I could have said the same

01:01:04.329 --> 01:01:06.190
thing in the prayer to the
Virgin;

01:01:06.190 --> 01:01:09.730
Virgin, mother,
daughter of your son;

01:01:09.730 --> 01:01:14.530
two birds in one stone,
in half a line as it were.

01:01:14.530 --> 01:01:18.210
Daughter of your son,
Dante focuses on birth.

01:01:18.210 --> 01:01:20.869
I did say, I went on talking
since--

01:01:20.869 --> 01:01:22.380
Dante talks like this about
Virgil,

01:01:22.380 --> 01:01:25.840
then talks about the birth of
Francesca,

01:01:25.840 --> 01:01:30.070
Giacco in Canto VI,
Farinata in Canto X,

01:01:30.070 --> 01:01:32.429
endlessly talks about this
whole issue.

01:01:32.429 --> 01:01:36.871
Then I went on talking,
this concern with birth is

01:01:36.871 --> 01:01:39.500
specifically Roman,
I said.

01:01:39.500 --> 01:01:44.757
This is really a Roman insight
into the importance--it's really

01:01:44.757 --> 01:01:49.929
what distinguishes the Greek
tragic understanding of birth.

01:01:49.929 --> 01:01:52.500
Children can really become a
curse in--

01:01:52.500 --> 01:01:56.268
when you read the
Thebaid, for instance,

01:01:56.268 --> 01:01:57.929
where you read the story of
Oedipus,

01:01:57.929 --> 01:02:02.349
with Statius being half Greek,
sort of incorporates.

01:02:02.349 --> 01:02:05.007
Then I added,
after saying that this a Roman

01:02:05.007 --> 01:02:08.407
concern, because it's the
whole--it's tied to the notion

01:02:08.407 --> 01:02:09.518
of foundation.
 

01:02:09.518 --> 01:02:12.987
The Roman idea that you can
start things over and over again

01:02:12.987 --> 01:02:16.514
with the foundations of cities
and the birth being the way in

01:02:16.514 --> 01:02:19.498
which nature becomes historical,
and therefore,

01:02:19.498 --> 01:02:22.445
I potentially like all of you
potentially can change

01:02:22.445 --> 01:02:23.889
everything around you.
 

01:02:23.889 --> 01:02:26.188
It's not true,
as someone at a round table the

01:02:26.188 --> 01:02:29.050
other night in my department,
was saying that you have no

01:02:29.050 --> 01:02:30.889
experience, there are no events.
 

01:02:30.889 --> 01:02:33.219
Of course there are experiences
and events,

01:02:33.219 --> 01:02:36.400
every birth is an event,
that's Dante's understanding

01:02:36.400 --> 01:02:39.469
because he can change history,
he can change the future.

01:02:39.469 --> 01:02:42.545
After making these statements
that that's a Roman idea,

01:02:42.545 --> 01:02:45.280
and or Dante that's crucial
because he's a Roman,

01:02:45.280 --> 01:02:47.559
and he thinks of himself as a
Roman;

01:02:47.559 --> 01:02:50.268
Florence is the daughter of
Rome.

01:02:50.268 --> 01:02:55.699
Then I added that this is also
a Jewish idea of creation.

01:02:55.699 --> 01:02:59.186
That that's really what we
have, mainly the great invention

01:02:59.186 --> 01:03:03.588
that we have in the Bible,
that the world was created and

01:03:03.588 --> 01:03:06.869
that Dante is connecting two
ideas,

01:03:06.869 --> 01:03:10.677
a Roman and a Jewish idea,
which are miraculously

01:03:10.677 --> 01:03:11.710
convergent.
 

01:03:11.710 --> 01:03:16.000
Is this an act of useful
patience because that's really

01:03:16.000 --> 01:03:18.860
the--what I read in your
question.

01:03:18.860 --> 01:03:21.065
Is that an appropriation?
 

01:03:21.065 --> 01:03:22.300
It's culture.
 

01:03:22.300 --> 01:03:25.625
I think that that's really what
you do, but you can say that

01:03:25.625 --> 01:03:26.639
about the Bible.
 

01:03:26.639 --> 01:03:30.514
You read, the Bible is a
reading of history,

01:03:30.514 --> 01:03:33.760
over 800 years of its
composition.

01:03:33.760 --> 01:03:37.949
It's a reading of events around
them and the culture,

01:03:37.949 --> 01:03:40.929
and that's exactly what Dante
does.

01:03:40.929 --> 01:03:46.650
How does he look at--he thinks
that the Jews--

01:03:46.650 --> 01:03:50.259
I guess he's really saying they
are not Christians but they

01:03:50.259 --> 01:03:53.619
believe in a Christ to come and
that will save them.

01:03:53.619 --> 01:03:58.393
This really means that there is
an acknowledgement of the

01:03:58.393 --> 01:04:02.739
dignity and certainly
originality of that vision.

01:04:02.739 --> 01:04:05.291
I answered clearly;
you may agree,

01:04:05.291 --> 01:04:07.349
you may not agree,
but it's clear.

01:04:07.349 --> 01:04:08.840
We agree about that.
 

01:04:21.840 --> 01:04:30.608
Student:  I was
wondering if you could just

01:04:30.608 --> 01:04:34.023
brief--
I was wondering if you could

01:04:34.023 --> 01:04:38.148
discuss the presence of violence
in all of these texts that we've

01:04:38.148 --> 01:04:39.179
been reading.
 

01:04:39.179 --> 01:04:44.166
I'm thinking particularly about
the Vita nuova and the

01:04:44.166 --> 01:04:49.155
depiction of violence in these
dreams filled with passion and

01:04:49.155 --> 01:04:54.059
very strange representations of
the color red and all--

01:04:54.059 --> 01:04:59.141
as both a lustful color,
the fear of death in these

01:04:59.141 --> 01:05:05.643
depictions of love which reminds
me of courtly love and this idea

01:05:05.643 --> 01:05:12.250
that our passions are sort of
transcendental violent dreams,

01:05:12.250 --> 01:05:14.079
and images that come to us.
 

01:05:14.079 --> 01:05:17.398
That's one question,
one part, but the other is the

01:05:17.398 --> 01:05:21.579
presence of violence and violent
imagery in Paradiso,

01:05:21.579 --> 01:05:25.699
I'm thinking particularly about
marshes at the beginning in

01:05:25.699 --> 01:05:26.409
Canto I?
 

01:05:26.409 --> 01:05:31.657
Also, the implied moral
violation of Piccarda and these

01:05:31.657 --> 01:05:37.878
continuous images that remind us
of human violence and passion as

01:05:37.878 --> 01:05:42.855
violence,
and I wonder how they fit in

01:05:42.855 --> 01:05:49.440
with the final vision of
beatitude and human love?

01:05:49.440 --> 01:05:55.280
Prof: That brings us
right back to the relationship

01:05:55.280 --> 01:05:59.380
between the historical and the
sacred.

01:05:59.380 --> 01:06:05.960
Violence is a parody almost of
the sacred,

01:06:05.960 --> 01:06:09.041
and in many ways,
the alibi for the sacred

01:06:09.041 --> 01:06:13.400
because the sacred has to be
understood as that which tries

01:06:13.400 --> 01:06:15.429
to redeem the violence.
 

01:06:15.429 --> 01:06:20.753
And Dante, you're absolutely
right, never flinches from the

01:06:20.753 --> 01:06:26.262
understanding that the world of
history is an economy of this

01:06:26.262 --> 01:06:27.822
ongoing violence.
 

01:06:27.822 --> 01:06:29.199
It's true.
 

01:06:29.199 --> 01:06:35.010
He even addresses you, right.
 

01:06:35.010 --> 01:06:39.170
The human beings,
the Cato who kills himself

01:06:39.170 --> 01:06:44.782
hoping that with his death he
can bring an end to the civil

01:06:44.782 --> 01:06:49.039
war in Rome between Caesar and
Pompeii,

01:06:49.039 --> 01:06:53.518
but then the violence
that--someone like Piccarda.

01:06:53.518 --> 01:06:57.152
How love engenders violence,
it's an incredibly thing,

01:06:57.152 --> 01:06:59.690
because then they have
perversions.

01:06:59.690 --> 01:07:03.827
It's not just that I killed
because I want to steal

01:07:03.827 --> 01:07:07.360
someone's shoes,
but then there is a way in

01:07:07.360 --> 01:07:12.190
which I think I'm engaged a more
tragic understanding of violence

01:07:12.190 --> 01:07:15.815
because a sort it--
it's so mediated and so

01:07:15.815 --> 01:07:17.440
disguised as love.
 

01:07:17.440 --> 01:07:21.583
I can love, from Paolo and
Francesca, and yet that

01:07:21.583 --> 01:07:24.119
engenders a lot of violence.
 

01:07:24.119 --> 01:07:28.500
Dante has gone through all the
phases for this sort of

01:07:28.500 --> 01:07:29.409
thinking.
 

01:07:29.409 --> 01:07:32.507
That of thinking that maybe
that's really what history is

01:07:32.507 --> 01:07:35.338
about;
it's all about violence and

01:07:35.338 --> 01:07:40.666
that any effort at redemption,
Christ's redemption of

01:07:40.666 --> 01:07:47.023
violence, that's really what the
whole story of Christian

01:07:47.023 --> 01:07:49.518
salvation is about.
 

01:07:49.518 --> 01:07:52.630
Dante mentions that,
this is not a kind of an

01:07:52.630 --> 01:07:56.730
opinion, Dante will mention it
in Inferno XXXIII.

01:07:56.730 --> 01:08:00.760
Remember, with the story of
Ugolino,

01:08:00.760 --> 01:08:05.351
in the background of that
scene, of that famous

01:08:05.351 --> 01:08:09.246
cannibalizing,
that is the story of the

01:08:09.246 --> 01:08:13.182
children have been killed,
two of his children,

01:08:13.182 --> 01:08:17.028
and that's always the death of
the innocent is really the

01:08:17.028 --> 01:08:19.279
beginning--
what happens to the children?

01:08:19.279 --> 01:08:22.908
We can go on arguing but what
about these kids?

01:08:22.908 --> 01:08:25.569
We have no response of what is
innocent as Dante says,

01:08:25.569 --> 01:08:28.760
and then you overhear in the
background,

01:08:28.760 --> 01:08:33.712
and I think that Dante wants us
to overhear the experience of

01:08:33.712 --> 01:08:38.333
the cross that was meant to
redeem of violence but didn't

01:08:38.333 --> 01:08:41.992
seem to work,
so there is a way in which he

01:08:41.992 --> 01:08:45.720
thinks violence has--
to the notion and to the god of

01:08:45.720 --> 01:08:50.060
violence,
even the redemption succumbs to

01:08:50.060 --> 01:08:51.569
that vision.
 

01:08:51.569 --> 01:08:56.658
The idea of redemption loses in
connection with--and in relation

01:08:56.658 --> 01:08:57.788
to violence.
 

01:08:57.788 --> 01:09:04.060
That would be the way we can
come to understand it.

01:09:04.060 --> 01:09:06.180
There are a number of other
extensions,

01:09:06.180 --> 01:09:10.390
even when we read Dante will
say, when we read,

01:09:10.390 --> 01:09:13.494
it seems to be such an
innocuous bland operation that

01:09:13.494 --> 01:09:17.194
we're engaged in,
in the quiet of our studies,

01:09:17.194 --> 01:09:21.934
etc., then we are still
violating the integrity of the

01:09:21.934 --> 01:09:22.649
text.
 

01:09:22.649 --> 01:09:26.220
We still extract,
we still break up that unity,

01:09:26.220 --> 01:09:30.970
we isolate the passage,
we make part of what we want,

01:09:30.970 --> 01:09:34.720
what we want it to signify,
hermeneutics is linked,

01:09:34.720 --> 01:09:37.340
interpretation is linked to an
experience of violence.

01:09:37.340 --> 01:09:38.899
What gives?
 

01:09:38.899 --> 01:09:41.904
We agree there,
that was your question,

01:09:41.904 --> 01:09:46.729
how does Dante get beyond that
and somehow manage to arrive to

01:09:46.729 --> 01:09:48.470
a beatific vision?
 

01:09:48.470 --> 01:09:53.368
I think that what Dante is
doing is denouncing all forms of

01:09:53.368 --> 01:09:57.086
violence, confessing to them,
admitting them,

01:09:57.086 --> 01:09:58.859
dramatizing them.
 

01:09:58.859 --> 01:10:01.685
It doesn't mean that he's
espousing them or he shares

01:10:01.685 --> 01:10:04.028
them,
the whole point of the

01:10:04.028 --> 01:10:08.149
Divine Comedy is to
acknowledge that it lodges --

01:10:08.149 --> 01:10:11.850
it, violence -- lodges even in
him and within him,

01:10:11.850 --> 01:10:16.868
but he wants to move beyond it
and that's the ascetic aspect of

01:10:16.868 --> 01:10:20.252
his text,
ascetic in the sense that he's

01:10:20.252 --> 01:10:25.159
literally climbing up the ladder
of transcending that which is

01:10:25.159 --> 01:10:26.770
holding him back.
 

01:10:26.770 --> 01:10:30.868
I don't think that--if you are
looking for way that--does he

01:10:30.868 --> 01:10:32.189
get away from it?
 

01:10:32.189 --> 01:10:36.368
That's really the other
question, does he ever get away?

01:10:36.368 --> 01:10:40.712
Not in the measure in which
he's human and wants to remain

01:10:40.712 --> 01:10:44.369
human, open to these temptations
all the time.

01:10:53.289 --> 01:10:54.449
Please.
 

01:11:01.260 --> 01:11:05.228
Student:  As a pilgrim
who has become a senior citizen

01:11:05.228 --> 01:11:08.800
I have had a question throughout
the entire course,

01:11:08.800 --> 01:11:13.341
and having read Auerbach and
Thomas Bergen and Mary Reynolds

01:11:13.341 --> 01:11:15.743
and others,
the question has not been

01:11:15.743 --> 01:11:18.340
answered for me and I'm not sure
you can either.

01:11:18.340 --> 01:11:22.760
The question is who is Dante?
 

01:11:22.760 --> 01:11:25.623
As we've been responding to
these--you've been responding to

01:11:25.623 --> 01:11:28.527
these questions here,
I've jotted down human,

01:11:28.527 --> 01:11:31.306
man, citizen,
exile, lover,

01:11:31.306 --> 01:11:34.729
poet, pilgrim,
visionary,

01:11:34.729 --> 01:11:42.640
theologian, saint,
Paul, Teresa of Avila,

01:11:42.640 --> 01:11:45.198
John of the Cross,
Bernard of Clairvaux had their

01:11:45.198 --> 01:11:46.960
visions and they became saints.
 

01:11:46.960 --> 01:11:48.470
Is this man a saint?
 

01:11:48.470 --> 01:11:56.746
Prof: Well,
I'm taking a little bit of time

01:11:56.746 --> 01:12:04.300
to answer because you must know;
I think you know that actually

01:12:04.300 --> 01:12:07.680
there are people who think that
he should be canonized.

01:12:07.680 --> 01:12:09.399
You probably do not know that.
 

01:12:09.399 --> 01:12:11.770
Who think that he should be
canonized.

01:12:11.770 --> 01:12:14.712
Actually, I was actually
interviewed once about

01:12:14.712 --> 01:12:16.118
soliciting my ideas.
 

01:12:16.118 --> 01:12:21.163
I said I hope not because I
want to teach him for what I

01:12:21.163 --> 01:12:24.923
think he is a poet,
a man of extraordinary

01:12:24.923 --> 01:12:28.408
imagination who divinies our
time.

01:12:28.408 --> 01:12:31.658
That's what I think he is,
the power of the imagination,

01:12:31.658 --> 01:12:36.416
and who understands that the
greatest call on him and on us

01:12:36.416 --> 01:12:41.420
is really the possibility of the
encounter with the Divine.

01:12:41.420 --> 01:12:44.530
I don't know--I hate the
idea--if I were to make a movie

01:12:44.530 --> 01:12:47.280
about Dante--
I have been--sometimes when

01:12:47.280 --> 01:12:51.904
people have been--
I have been mentioning it to

01:12:51.904 --> 01:12:59.411
people actually I would make him
into a rebellious type who seems

01:12:59.411 --> 01:13:04.689
to understand everything that he
touches,

01:13:04.689 --> 01:13:08.546
but he also has a way and
takes, as he should from

01:13:08.546 --> 01:13:10.975
everything,
and transforms it,

01:13:10.975 --> 01:13:14.220
so he has a vision from that
point of view.

01:13:14.220 --> 01:13:18.270
The vision of how the world is
and--he invents the world,

01:13:18.270 --> 01:13:21.744
his world, the world of the
Divine Comedy,

01:13:21.744 --> 01:13:24.350
